29#ifndef ISCCC_SYMTAB_H
30#define ISCCC_SYMTAB_H 1
31
32/*****
33 ***** Module Info
34 *****/
35
36/*! \file isccc/symtab.h
37 * \brief
38 * Provides a simple memory-based symbol table.
39 *
40 * Keys are C strings. A type may be specified when looking up,
41 * defining, or undefining. A type value of 0 means "match any type";
42 * any other value will only match the given type.
43 *
44 * It's possible that a client will attempt to define a <key, type,
45 * value> tuple when a tuple with the given key and type already
46 * exists in the table. What to do in this case is specified by the
47 * client. Possible policies are:
48 *
49 *\li isccc_symexists_reject Disallow the define, returning #ISC_R_EXISTS
50 *\li isccc_symexists_replace Replace the old value with the new. The
51 * undefine action (if provided) will be called
52 * with the old <key, type, value> tuple.
53 *\li isccc_symexists_add Add the new tuple, leaving the old tuple in
54 * the table. Subsequent lookups will retrieve
55 * the most-recently-defined tuple.
56 *
57 * A lookup of a key using type 0 will return the most-recently
58 * defined symbol with that key. An undefine of a key using type 0
59 * will undefine the most-recently defined symbol with that key.
60 * Trying to define a key with type 0 is illegal.
61 *
62 * The symbol table library does not make a copy the key field, so the
63 * caller must ensure that any key it passes to isccc_symtab_define()
64 * will not change until it calls isccc_symtab_undefine() or
65 * isccc_symtab_destroy().
66 *
67 * A user-specified action will be called (if provided) when a symbol
68 * is undefined. It can be used to free memory associated with keys
69 * and/or values.
70 */
71
72/***
73 *** Imports.
74 ***/
75
76#include <stdbool.h>
77
78#include <isc/lang.h>
79#include <isccc/types.h>
80
81/***
82 *** Symbol Tables.
83 ***/
84
85typedef union isccc_symvalue {
86 void * as_pointer;
87 int as_integer;
88 unsigned int as_uinteger;
89} isccc_symvalue_t;
90
91typedef void (*isccc_symtabundefaction_t)(char *key, unsigned int type,
92 isccc_symvalue_t value, void *userarg);
93
94typedef bool (*isccc_symtabforeachaction_t)(char *key,
95 unsigned int type,
96 isccc_symvalue_t value,
97 void *userarg);
98
99typedef enum {
100 isccc_symexists_reject = 0,
101 isccc_symexists_replace = 1,
102 isccc_symexists_add = 2
103} isccc_symexists_t;
104
105ISC_LANG_BEGINDECLS
106
107isc_result_t
108isccc_symtab_create(unsigned int size,
109 isccc_symtabundefaction_t undefine_action, void *undefine_arg,
110 bool case_sensitive, isccc_symtab_t **symtabp);
111
112void
113isccc_symtab_destroy(isccc_symtab_t **symtabp);
114
115isc_result_t
116isccc_symtab_lookup(isccc_symtab_t *symtab, const char *key, unsigned int type,
117 isccc_symvalue_t *value);
118
119isc_result_t
120isccc_symtab_define(isccc_symtab_t *symtab, char *key, unsigned int type,
121 isccc_symvalue_t value, isccc_symexists_t exists_policy);
122
123isc_result_t
124isccc_symtab_undefine(isccc_symtab_t *symtab, const char *key, unsigned int type);
125
126void
127isccc_symtab_foreach(isccc_symtab_t *symtab, isccc_symtabforeachaction_t action,
128 void *arg);
129
130ISC_LANG_ENDDECLS
131
132#endif /* ISCCC_SYMTAB_H */
